Before coating, the surface of Mg-2Ca (Sup. 
                        Fig. 2
                        ) was gradually ground using SiC grit papers (Gravimeta) up to a final grit of P1000. Samples were rinsed with ethanol, followed by compressed air drying. The Mg-2Ca coupons were immersed in a solution of 2.5% (w/v) of PCL (MW = 14,000, Sigma-Aldrich) dissolved in a water-miscible organic solvent, N,N-dimethylformamide (Fluka).

Quite different profiles of the corrosion layer can be observed (Fig. 4 and 5). All the samples showed the presence of C, O, Mg, Cl, and Ca in the corrosion layer (Fig. 4a and 5 a, d). In the sample coated with PCL-TiO2, the additional identification of P in the corrosion layer highlights the difference in the degradation process in this sample (Fig. 5
                        d), leading to the formation of distinct degradation products when immersed in DMEM. When looking in detail at the surface of each sample (Fig. 4b and 5 b, e), several morphological differences can be observed. In the corroded Mg-2Ca sample, a rough surface can be observed either by the dissolution of Mg and Ca or by the precipitation of the corrosion layer (Fig. 4b). Three distinct morphologies can be observed, plates (Fig. 4b i), cubic (Fig. 4b ii), and needle-like (Fig. 4b iii) structures. The predominant plate-like structure (Fig. 4b i), with a prevailing composition of Mg and O (Table 2
                        ), can be related to brucite formation [Mg(OH)2] [49,50], a product formed upon Mg degradation that typically presents a cracked texture due to dehydrating [51,52]. The cubic structure depicted in Fig. 4b ii), coincident with the presence of C (Table 2), has been assigned to carbonates, naturally formed by the alkalinization of the medium and CO2 diffusion in the electrolyte [43,53,54]. The needle-like structures (Fig. 4b iii), rich in Cl (Table 2), are characteristic of magnesium oxychloride [nMg(OH)2.Mg.Cl2] [55,56]. Similarly, the round-to-cubic forms depicted in the degraded PCL coated samples in Fig. 5b iv), with a high C content (Table 2), can be related to carbonated species formation. Due to the cracked-like morphology, the structural features depicted in Fig. 5b v), and the high O content (Table 2) can be related to the formation of brucite. The rough structure observed in the degraded PCL coated sample (Fig. 5b vi) resembles hydrated PCL pieces, an observation corroborated by the large C content. In the presence of the PCL-TiO2 coating, the same needle-like structure together with considerable Cl amounts (Table 2) can be again assigned to the precipitation of magnesium oxychloride (Fig. 5f ix). The new lamina-like form observed in Fig. 5f vii); alongside with high O and C levels (Table 2), can be related to brucite and/or carbonates precipitation. Depending on factors such as pH and [Mg2+], different carbonate morphologies may exist [53]. The sphere-like agglomerates (Fig. 5f viii) with a high content of P and Ca (Table 2), exclusively formed on the PCL-TiO2 surface, are in line with the precipitation of hydrogen phosphates and/or apatites [57]. Studies on TiO2-based ceramics proved that the nucleation of calcium and phosphorus to form hydroxyapatite is favored in the presence of these oxides [1,58-60]. Kitsugi et al. [58] reported that TiO2 coated titanium alloy implants directly bonded to bone tissue leading to the development of a Ca-P layer at the interface of the coated implants and the bone. Likewise, Ramírez-Cedillo et al. [59] reported that the presence of TiO2 in PCL fibrous membranes promoted the formation of apatite-like clusters in simulated physiological conditions and that the PCL nanocomposite with higher TiO2 concentration had the highest nucleation rate of apatite formation [1]. Apatites, with important osteoconductive properties, are essential to ensure the success of the implanted material [61,62], thus indicating that PCL-TiO2 coatings may favor osseointegration and tissue regeneration [1] upon implantation.
